[Drought can be devastating to animals for a number of reasons. Forage is in short supply for the animals and for making hay. Toxic plants can get baled into hay and in such a fashion the animal are not able to avoid the toxic plants. Furthermore, hungry or thirsty animals will eat plants they would normally avoid.

Water, or lack thereof, can also be a problem. Toxic substances such as blue green algae may propagate in ponds. The blue green algae may increase in concentration as the drought reduces the volume of the water. So, water may be come toxic as well.

There is not enough evidence presented in this article to know what type of plants are being suggested as the possible cause of death of these animals. - Mod.TG

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/1iSZ.]

